---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Eyebrow from "../components/Eyebrow.astro";
import Button from "../components/Button.astro";
import FlowSnippet from "../components/FlowSnippet.astro";
import BlockCard from "../components/BlockCard.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import Chip from "../components/Chip.astro";
import { type BlockCategory } from "../lib/flow";

const gateFlow: { label: string; category: BlockCategory }[] = [
  { label: "Summarize", category: "synthesis" },
  { label: "Gate", category: "control" },
  { label: "Send", category: "action" },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How it works — Arachne"
  description="Sketch a rough pipeline, run it on real data, and harden it as the process reveals itself. Blocks declare their effects, files carry provenance, and humans hold the steps that aren't delegable."
>
  <!-- HEADER -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <Eyebrow>How it works</Eyebrow>
      <h1>You build the flow by running it.</h1>
      <p class="lead measure">
        A flow starts as a sketch and hardens into an audited workflow. Blocks
        declare what they consume, emit, and change; every file carries a
        provenance chain back to source; and the steps a person must own pause
        for that person. The same tool runs a first draft and the mature
        version it becomes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 1. SKETCH → REFINE → FORMALIZE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container measure">
      <Eyebrow>Sketch · Refine · Formalize</Eyebrow>
      <h2>Formalization is a journey, not a prerequisite.</h2>
      <p class="stack-p">
        A sketch block declares the rough shape of a step and stands up a
        working pipeline in minutes — good enough to run on real data and hand
        to a teammate. You don't have to specify everything before you start.
      </p>
      <p class="stack-p">
        You harden it incrementally, as the process reveals itself. Add schema
        enforcement where you've learned the data's shape. Add a Gate where the
        naive automation keeps getting it wrong. Replace a sketch block with a
        fully typed, validated block once you know exactly what it should do.
      </p>
      <p>
        The same tool runs a first-pass pipeline for a two-person team and a
        mature, audited, multi-stage workflow for an enterprise. The difference
        between them is how much of the flow you've formalized — not which
        product you bought.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 2. BLOCKS, EFFECTS, PROVENANCE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <Eyebrow>Blocks · Effects · Provenance</Eyebrow>
      <h2>Two data types, declared effects, an unbroken chain.</h2>
      <p class="measure stack-p">
        All data is one of two types. A Document is natural language — Markdown,
        plain text, or HTML — and is the input to AI blocks. A Record is JSON
        with addressable fields, and is the input to deterministic logic. Every
        block declares which it accepts and which it emits; a type mismatch
        renders as an unverified connection on the canvas, before it runs.
      </p>
      <div class="cards">
        <BlockCard
          category="extraction"
          name="Extract Insights"
          effect="pure · deterministic"
        />
        <BlockCard category="action" name="Send" effect="effect: Send" />
      </div>
      <p class="measure stack-p">
        Every block declares its purity and determinism, and effects propagate
        along the graph — so you can see, before a run, which steps reach out
        and touch the world. Every file then carries an append-only provenance
        chain: which block produced it, from which inputs, at what time, using
        what configuration, including the prompt version. AI outputs additionally
        reference the specific source passages supporting each claim. Provenance
        is never stripped, and a block cannot modify it.
      </p>
      <div class="prov measure">
        <CodeBlock file="flow.json">{`"provenance": [
  {
    "block": "summarize-3",
    "inputs": ["report.md"],
    "at": "2026-05-28T14:02:11Z",
    "config": { "prompt_version": "summarize@4" }
  }
]`}</CodeBlock>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 3. HUMANS ARE FIRST-CLASS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container split">
      <div class="measure">
        <Eyebrow>Humans are first-class</Eyebrow>
        <h2>Some judgments are not delegable.</h2>
        <p class="stack-p">
          A Gate or Manual Input block pauses execution, routes a structured
          task to the right person, and resumes when they've acted. The flow
          holds at that step — it does not guess, and it does not proceed
          without the decision.
        </p>
        <p>
          A waiting step carries the <Chip state="needs-input" /> chip on the
          canvas, so the held decision is visible, not buried. Accountability is
          not transferable; the tool routes it rather than absorbing it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="snippet-wrap">
        <FlowSnippet
          nodes={gateFlow}
          caption="A Gate holds for human review between drafting and sending."
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 4. ERRORS PRODUCE DURABLE FIXES -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container measure">
      <Eyebrow>Errors produce durable fixes</Eyebrow>
      <h2>A mistake becomes a change, not a recurrence.</h2>
      <p class="stack-p">
        When a flow makes a mistake, the error surfaces with full context: the
        exact block that failed, the input it received, the output it produced,
        and the provenance chain back to source. You're debugging a step, not
        re-reading a transcript.
      </p>
      <p>
        You identify the step that needs to change, make a targeted fix, verify
        it on the canvas, and deploy it knowing it applies consistently to every
        future run. The change is legible in the version history — what changed,
        when, and why.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CLOSE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container measure">
      <Button href="/ownership" variant="ghost">Read about ownership</Button>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  h1 {
    margin-top: var(--s-16);
    max-width: 22ch;
  }
  .lead {
    margin-top: var(--s-24);
  }

  h2 {
    max-width: 24ch;
  }
  .stack-p {
    margin-bottom: var(--s-16);
  }
  .section p {
    margin-top: var(--s-16);
  }

  .cards {
    margin-top: var(--s-32);
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--s-16);
  }
  .prov {
    margin-top: var(--s-24);
  }

  .split {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1.1fr 0.9fr;
    gap: var(--s-40);
    align-items: center;
  }
  .snippet-wrap {
    background: var(--bg-1);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-0);
    border-radius: var(--r-10);
    padding: var(--s-32) var(--s-24);
  }

  @media (max-width: 860px) {
    .split {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
